text: "But when the fantasies turn into nightmares, the guests have to solve the islandâ€™s mystery in order to escape with their lives" Do they have to 'solve the island' or do they have to have a epiphany about themselves, let go, and move forward? The old show and the 90's reboot the guests did have dangerous fantasies but usually had a reflection and left the island to be better people.  Still a case of 'careful what you think you want' situations and did have some dark turns but also some silly ones (variety of different fantasies meant different takes and style to them).  This seems to focus only on the horror and dark side aspects. Don't know if Mr. Roarke wants the bad things and final outcomes to happen to the guests out of evil/ritual or does want to help the guests overcome their psychological situations with the island's magic even if it might be dark or even dangerous.  I predict the mother will learn to let go of her lost daughter.  The other lady maybe to forgive and let go of her revenge that will end the fantasy and have her leaving to connect that woman to have a healthy talk.  The others I'll have to discover a bit more context to the fantasy and what sparked it.

text: I wish this wasn't just a horror movie. The beauty of Fantasy Island was the variety of stories it could tell given the setting. True, some of the stories were dark, but you also had lighthearted stories as well, sometimes in the same episode as a more serious story to break the tension.  And the overall tone of the original show was lighthearted, what with the interactions between Mr. Roarke and Tatu. This remake clearly did not care for its source material and just wanted to use the name and setting to make a cheap run-of-the-mill horror movie.  And if you think it's not possible to tell stories of various genres in a single movie, look at The Twilight Zone movie from 1983, a movie based on a classic anthology TV show that told stories from a variety of genres. I'm not saying that Fantasy Island 2020 should follow the same format, just that they treat the series with just as much dignity.

text: I can't take this seriously due to 7 rings. The song is catchy but has no place in this trailer unless it's a cheesy comedy. Ariana is portrayed thus far as a disrespectful, spoiled diva. With a voice that could shatter glass (in a bad way), make anyone's ears bleed & earns her the title of a living dog whistle. It turns me off to the movie completely & makes me wish I'd gone deaf.  Sony, If in the 1 in a million chance you see this, I love Blumhouse but, Instead of horror, a psychological thriller, or whatever it's supposed to be, it reads as a bad joke. If hilarious stupidity is what you're going for, mission accomplished.   Lord Of The Rings, Jurassic Park, Jaws, The Breakfast Club, Harry Potter, Indiana Jones, etc. Are timeless classics & an important part of that are their scores. Summary; Marketing research exists for a reason, I feel like some old, rich white man was like, "now THIS is what the kids are into! The annoying, second-rate carbon copy of Mariah Carey from nickelodeon who's (like all childhood actors) doomed to fail".    IMPORTANT NOTE!    Before you get your panties in a twist, please understand this. I truly believe childhood actors aren't handled properly & many times their worst personality traits are unjustly magnified by paparazzi vultures & more than likely aren't their own fault due to being used, abused, neglected & exploited by their own family or others in the industry at a very vulnerable age where they're thrown into a fast-paced, stressful & (many times) toxic lifestyle for any child under 18 way before they should be asked to make important life-changing decisions for themselves to shape their future. Many times they are forced into giving answers & consenting to things that even some adults don't fully grasp or understand. Ignorant or just flat out greedy parents/guirdians sign their child's life away in the form of (practically) legal slave contracts to large corporations who milk them for wealth. They're thrrust into environments where, without proper supervision they're exposed to harmful coping mechanisms such as drugs at an age they should be experiencing a normal, innocent childhood & learning to distinguish right from wrong to try & relieve the unbelievable amount of stress suddenly pushed on them, usually by the people they were supposed to be able to trust.  The above is truly my opinion, I just like to make sure I don't come across TOO ignorant although random internet people's opinions aren't exactly what I live for. I think once in a while it's nice to see both sides of the coin from a single person. Cheers.

text: I let some comments about how I really liked this movie as a change from the Original one. I forgot to mention from the moment that actress Lucy Hale ( she plays Melanie), got off the plane I was taken aback because I actually thought she was Drew Barrymore. When she turned a certain way and had the same facial expressions that Drew has. I had to go back and look at the cast line up. Thats how I found out who played in the role of Melanie. Its got the twist at the end and I really was on the edge of my seat at times. All the actors played their roles perfectly,  and I was at the end trying to decide if Rourke  was a good guy that had a tough break, or a bad guy. I came to feel sorry for him. But really loved the ending and it almost let it open for a movie 2. I would DEFFINATLY watch it. But I would want Michael Pena to again play Mr. Rourke and Of course the actor who played Brax , Jimmy O. Yang, to play Tattoo. Again really loved this movie and will be watching it again to see if I missed anything the first watch around...
